## After This Lecture You Will Be Able To:

1. **Differentiate** epidural vs subdural — CT shape, prognosis
2. **Classify** spinal cord syndromes; apply NEXUS/CCR
3. **Calculate** Parkland formula; burn transfer criteria
4. **Apply** hemothorax, pelvic, penetrating trauma thresholds
5. **Recognize** compartment syndrome; Gustilo grades
6. **Modify** algorithms — pediatric, geriatric, pregnant

> **Bottom Line:** Ten trauma domains, six objectives, one shelf exam

<!-- Speaker Notes: These six learning objectives map directly to the highest-yield trauma topics on the NBME Surgery Subject Exam that are NOT covered in the companion xABCDE Primary Survey lecture. Objective one addresses the classic radiology question — you will see a CT image and must differentiate epidural from subdural hematoma based on shape, location, and clinical context. Objective two covers spinal cord syndromes, which test your ability to localize a lesion based on deficit pattern, plus the decision rules for clearing a c-spine. Objective three is pure calculation — the Parkland formula is a shelf favorite, and the most common error is calculating from arrival time rather than burn time. Objective four addresses the operative thresholds that drive management decisions in chest, pelvic, and penetrating trauma. Objective five covers two orthopedic emergencies where timing is critical — compartment syndrome has a 6-hour window and open fractures require antibiotics within one hour. Objective six addresses the three special populations where standard trauma algorithms require modification. Each section concludes with an MCQ that tests the concept in NBME stem format. Use the Shelf Tips throughout to identify the testing pattern before you see it on exam day. -->

