## Epidural and Subdural Hematomas Have Opposite CT Patterns and Prognoses

| Feature | Epidural | Subdural |
|---------|----------|----------|
| **Source** | Middle meningeal artery | Bridging veins |
| **CT shape** | Biconvex | Crescent |
| **History** | Lucid interval | Gradual decline |
| **Population** | Young, temporal fx | Elderly, anticoagulated |
| **Surgery** | >1 cm / >30 mL / shift | >10 mm / >5 mm shift |
| **Prognosis** | Good (early evacuation) | 40-60% mortality |

**[KEY STAT: Epidural = biconvex + lucid interval; subdural = crescent + elderly]**

> **Bottom Line:** CT shape alone distinguishes epidural from subdural


**Sources:**
- [1] Bullock 2006
- [2] Bullock 2006

<!-- Speaker Notes: This is one of the most frequently tested radiology questions on the surgery shelf. The epidural hematoma classically presents in a young patient with a temporal bone fracture who ruptures the middle meningeal artery. The classic history is a lucid interval — the patient is initially conscious after the injury, then rapidly deteriorates as the arterial bleed expands. On CT, the epidural appears as a biconvex or lens-shaped hyperdensity that does NOT cross suture lines because it is between the dura and the inner table of the skull. The subdural hematoma has the opposite pattern. It occurs in elderly patients, those on anticoagulants, or alcoholics with cerebral atrophy. The mechanism is tearing of bridging veins, and on CT it appears as a crescent-shaped collection that follows the brain surface and CAN cross suture lines. Acute subdurals carry a much worse prognosis at 40-60% mortality. Surgical thresholds differ: epidurals are evacuated when greater than 1 cm thickness, greater than 30 mL volume, or with midline shift. Subdurals are evacuated when greater than 10 mm thick or with greater than 5 mm midline shift. > **Shelf Tip:** When a stem shows a CT image and asks for diagnosis, look at the SHAPE first — biconvex is epidural, crescent is subdural. The age and history confirm but the shape is definitive. -->

