## BTF 4th Edition ICP Management Follows a 3-Tier Escalation Algorithm

| Tier | Interventions | Target |
|------|--------------|--------|
| **Tier 1** | HOB 30°, PaCO2 35-40, sedation, CSF drain | ICP <22 mmHg |
| **Tier 2** | HTS 23.4% / mannitol, PaCO2 30-35 | CPP 60-70 mmHg |
| **Tier 3** | Craniectomy, pentobarbital coma | Refractory ICP |

**[KEY STAT: ICP threshold <22 mmHg (updated from 20 in BTF 4th Edition)]**

> **Bottom Line:** Escalate tier-by-tier: position, then osmotherapy, then surgery


**Sources:**
- [3] Carney 2017
- [4] [Cooper 2011](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21434843/)

<!-- Speaker Notes: The Brain Trauma Foundation fourth edition guidelines, published by Carney and colleagues in 2017, updated the ICP treatment threshold from 20 to 22 mmHg based on new evidence. This is a commonly tested update. The three-tier system provides a systematic escalation algorithm. Tier one interventions are basic and should be implemented for all severe TBI patients: head of bed elevation to 30 degrees promotes venous drainage, normocapnia with PaCO2 of 35-40 maintains cerebral blood flow without causing vasoconstriction, sedation reduces metabolic demand, and CSF drainage via ventriculostomy directly reduces intracranial volume per the Monroe-Kellie doctrine. If ICP remains above 22 despite tier one, escalate to tier two. Osmotherapy with either 23.4% hypertonic saline or mannitol at 0.25-1 g/kg creates an osmotic gradient that pulls water from brain parenchyma into the vasculature. Mild hyperventilation to PaCO2 30-35 causes cerebral vasoconstriction and reduces intracranial blood volume, but should only be used as a bridge because sustained hyperventilation causes ischemia. Tier three is reserved for refractory ICP elevation. The DECRA trial (Cooper 2011, PMID 21434843) and RESCUEicp trial (Hutchinson 2016) showed that decompressive craniectomy reduces ICP and mortality but may increase rates of vegetative state. CPP target of 60-70 mmHg is maintained throughout. > **Shelf Tip:** When a stem asks about ICP management, identify which tier the patient is at and escalate to the next. The shelf tests whether you know the ORDER of interventions, not just the list. -->

