## Four Spinal Cord Syndromes Produce Distinct Deficit Patterns

| Syndrome | Mechanism | Lost | Preserved |
|----------|-----------|------|-----------|
| **Anterior cord** | Burst fx, aortic injury | Motor, pain, temp | Proprio, vibration |
| **Central cord** | Hyperextension (elderly) | Arms > legs | Sacral sensation |
| **Brown-Sequard** | Hemisection (penetrating) | Ipsi motor/proprio; contra pain/temp | — |
| **Cauda equina** | L1-L2 compression | Saddle anesthesia, bowel/bladder | **Surgical emergency** |

**[KEY STAT: Central cord = arms worse than legs in elderly hyperextension injury]**

> **Bottom Line:** Match the deficit pattern to the syndrome, then identify the mechanism


**Sources:**
- [6] Aarabi 2013
- [7] Fehlings 2012

<!-- Speaker Notes: Spinal cord syndromes are tested because they require you to localize a lesion based on the pattern of neurologic deficits. Each syndrome has a distinct mechanism and deficit profile. Anterior cord syndrome results from injury to the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, typically from burst fractures or aortic injury (the anterior spinal artery supplies this territory). Motor function, pain, and temperature are lost because the corticospinal tracts and spinothalamic tracts run anteriorly. Proprioception and vibration are preserved because the posterior columns are intact. Central cord syndrome is the most common incomplete cord injury and classically occurs in elderly patients with pre-existing cervical stenosis who sustain a hyperextension injury, often from a fall. The central gray matter is preferentially damaged, affecting the arms more than the legs because the upper extremity tracts are located more centrally in the cord. Sacral sensation is often spared. Brown-Sequard syndrome results from hemisection of the cord, most commonly from penetrating trauma. The deficit pattern reflects the anatomy of tract decussation: ipsilateral motor loss and proprioception loss (these tracts decussate in the brainstem), with contralateral pain and temperature loss (the spinothalamic tract crosses within one to two levels of entry). Cauda equina syndrome is a surgical emergency because the nerve roots below L1-L2 are peripheral nerves that can recover if decompressed early. Saddle anesthesia and bowel or bladder dysfunction are the hallmarks. > **Shelf Tip:** When a stem describes weakness in the arms greater than the legs after a fall in an elderly patient, the answer is central cord syndrome. This is the most commonly tested spinal cord syndrome. -->

