## Canadian C-Spine Rule Is More Sensitive and More Specific Than NEXUS

| Feature | NEXUS | CCR |
|---------|-------|-----|
| **Sensitivity** | 99.6% | 99.4-100% |
| **Specificity** | 12.9% | 45.1% |
| **Criteria** | 5 low-risk criteria | 3-step algorithm |
| **Preferred** | Universal | Alert, stable, ≥16 |
| **Obtunded** | CT alone (NPV >99%) | CT alone (NPV >99%) |

**[KEY STAT: CCR specificity 45.1% vs NEXUS 12.9% — fewer unnecessary CTs]**

> **Bottom Line:** CCR is preferred when applicable; CT alone clears obtunded patients


**Sources:**
- [8] [Hoffman 2000](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10891516/)
- [9] [Stiell 2003](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14695411/)
- [10] [Patel 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25757133/)

<!-- Speaker Notes: C-spine clearance decision rules are tested because the shelf wants to know that you can safely determine which trauma patients need imaging and which can be cleared clinically. NEXUS uses five criteria: no posterior midline tenderness, no intoxication, normal alertness with GCS of 15, no focal neurologic deficit, and no distracting injury. If all five are met, the c-spine can be cleared without imaging. The sensitivity is excellent at 99.6%, meaning almost no injuries are missed, but the specificity is poor at 12.9%, meaning most patients who do not have injuries still get imaged. The Canadian C-Spine Rule uses a three-step algorithm: first, are there high-risk factors mandating imaging (age over 65, dangerous mechanism, paresthesias)? If yes, image. If no, are there low-risk factors permitting range-of-motion assessment (simple rear-end MVC, sitting in ED, ambulatory, delayed onset neck pain, no midline tenderness)? If yes, assess range of motion. If the patient can actively rotate 45 degrees in each direction, the c-spine is cleared. The CCR is both more sensitive (99.4-100%) and more specific (45.1%), meaning it identifies injuries just as well while ordering significantly fewer unnecessary CT scans. The CCR is preferred when applicable but requires the patient to be alert and stable and age 16 or older. For the obtunded patient, the EAST guideline (Patel 2015, PMID 25757133) established that a high-quality CT alone is sufficient to clear the c-spine, with a negative predictive value greater than 99%. MRI is no longer routinely required. > **Shelf Tip:** When a stem asks about clearing a c-spine in an alert patient, CCR is the preferred tool. When the patient is obtunded, the answer is CT alone. -->

