## Neurogenic Shock = Hypotension + Bradycardia — The Opposite of Hypovolemic

- **Loss of sympathetic tone** above T6
- **Hypotension + bradycardia** + warm/vasodilated
- **Rx:** norepinephrine first-line, MAP >85 x 7 days
- **vs Spinal shock** — transient function loss, bulbocavernosus reflex return

**[KEY STAT: Bradycardia distinguishes neurogenic from hemorrhagic shock]**

> **Bottom Line:** Brady + hypotension + warm = neurogenic; tachy + hypotension + cold = hemorrhagic


**Sources:**
- [6] Aarabi 2013
- [7] Fehlings 2012
- [11] Hadley 2013

<!-- Speaker Notes: Neurogenic shock is one of the most commonly tested shock differentials on the shelf because it requires you to distinguish it from hemorrhagic shock based on hemodynamic findings. The mechanism is loss of sympathetic tone from a cervical or upper thoracic spinal cord injury above T6. Without sympathetic input, the patient loses vascular tone (causing vasodilation and hypotension) and loses cardiac sympathetic drive (causing bradycardia). This produces the classic triad: hypotension plus bradycardia plus warm, vasodilated extremities. Compare this to hemorrhagic shock, where the sympathetic system is intact and maximally activated: the patient has hypotension plus tachycardia plus cool, vasoconstricted extremities. The key distinguishing feature is the heart rate — bradycardia in the hypotensive trauma patient points to neurogenic shock. Treatment is vasopressors, with norepinephrine as the first-line agent because it provides both alpha (vasoconstriction) and beta-1 (chronotropic) effects. The target is MAP greater than 85 mmHg for seven days to optimize spinal cord perfusion. This is important because neurogenic shock is both a cardiovascular emergency requiring vasopressors AND must be distinguished from occult hemorrhage, which requires volume resuscitation. Spinal shock is a separate entity — it is the transient loss of all spinal cord function below the level of injury, including reflexes. It is a neurologic phenomenon, not a cardiovascular one. Resolution is marked by return of the bulbocavernosus reflex. > **Shelf Tip:** The shelf loves presenting a hypotensive trauma patient and asking you to identify the type of shock. Bradycardia is the single finding that distinguishes neurogenic from hemorrhagic. Do not let warm extremities alone fool you — always check the heart rate. -->

