<!-- type: Data/Table -->

**Gamma instruction: Data table, bold stats, high contrast**


## Rule of Nines Maps Body Surface Area — Pediatric Head Is Twice Adult Proportion

| Region | Adult % | Pediatric % |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| **Head** | 9% | 18% |
| **Each arm** | 9% | 9% |
| **Anterior trunk** | 18% | 18% |
| **Posterior trunk** | 18% | 18% |
| **Each leg** | 18% | 14% |
| **Perineum / Palm** | 1% / 1% TBSA | 1% / 1% TBSA |

**[KEY STAT: Pediatric head = 18% (2x adult) — legs proportionally smaller]**

> **Bottom Line:** Adults: head 9%, legs 18%; pediatrics: head 18%, legs 14%


**Sources:**
- [12] Baxter 1968
- [13] American 2006

<!-- Speaker Notes: The Rule of Nines is a rapid body surface area estimation tool used to calculate total body surface area burned, which drives fluid resuscitation calculations. The adult rule divides the body into regions that are multiples of nine: head is 9%, each upper extremity is 9%, anterior trunk is 18%, posterior trunk is 18%, each lower extremity is 18%, and the perineum is 1%, totaling 100%. The key pediatric modification is that the head is proportionally larger at 18% (twice the adult proportion), and the legs are proportionally smaller at 14% each. This reflects the pediatric body habitus where the head-to-body ratio is larger. This modification matters because using adult percentages on a child would underestimate head burns and overestimate leg burns, leading to incorrect fluid calculations. The palm method is useful for scattered or irregular burns: the patient's palm (including fingers) represents approximately 1% TBSA. This is used when burns do not conform neatly to the Rule of Nines regions. For Parkland formula calculations, only partial thickness and full thickness burns are included — superficial (first degree) burns are excluded from TBSA calculation. This is a common shelf error: including sunburn-type superficial burns in the TBSA calculation leads to over-resuscitation. The Lund-Browder chart is more accurate than the Rule of Nines, particularly in children, because it accounts for age-related body proportion changes, but the Rule of Nines is what the shelf tests because it is the rapid assessment tool used in the trauma bay. > **Shelf Tip:** When a pediatric burn stem is presented, remember head = 18% and legs = 14%. The shelf tests whether you use pediatric versus adult percentages by presenting a burned child and asking for TBSA calculation. -->

