<!-- type: Content -->

**Gamma instruction: Professional layout, bullet hierarchy, sources**


## Compartment Syndrome Has a 6-Hour Window — Pain with Passive Stretch Is the Earliest Sign

- **Most common:** tibial shaft fracture (anterior compartment)
- **6 Ps:** pain, passive stretch (**earliest**), paresthesias, paralysis, pulselessness (**late**)
- **Pressure** >30 or delta P <30 from diastolic
- **Rx:** emergent 4-compartment fasciotomy

**[KEY STAT: 6h window; pulselessness is LATE]**

> **Bottom Line:** Pain with passive stretch = fasciotomy, not more observation


**Sources:**
- [19] StatPearls
- [20] Gustilo 1976

<!-- Speaker Notes: Compartment syndrome is a time-critical surgical emergency tested on every surgery shelf exam. The mechanism is straightforward: increased pressure within a closed fascial compartment compromises perfusion to the muscles and nerves within that compartment, leading to ischemia and eventually irreversible necrosis. The most common scenario is a tibial shaft fracture affecting the anterior compartment of the lower leg, but it can occur in any fascial compartment including the forearm, thigh, and hand. The clinical findings follow the classic 6 Ps mnemonic, but the shelf specifically tests which findings are early and which are late. Pain out of proportion to the injury is the first symptom, and pain with passive stretch of the muscles in the affected compartment is the earliest and most reliable physical exam finding. For the anterior compartment of the leg, this means passive plantar flexion of the toes causes severe pain. Paresthesias follow as nerve ischemia develops. Paralysis indicates motor nerve death and is a late finding. Pallor and pulselessness are very late findings that indicate vascular compromise — if you wait for absent pulses, irreversible damage has already occurred. The diagnostic threshold is compartment pressure greater than 30 mmHg absolute, or a delta pressure (diastolic minus compartment pressure) less than 30 mmHg. However, the diagnosis is clinical, and fasciotomy should not be delayed for pressure measurements when the clinical picture is clear. Treatment is emergent fasciotomy of all four compartments of the lower leg: anterior, lateral, superficial posterior, and deep posterior. The time window is approximately 6 hours — beyond this, irreversible muscle necrosis (Volkmann contracture) and nerve damage occur. > **Shelf Tip:** The shelf will present a tibial fracture with severe pain and ask for the diagnosis or next step. Do NOT be distracted by answer choices checking pulses or ordering imaging. Pain with passive stretch = fasciotomy. -->

