<!-- type: Data/Table -->

**Gamma instruction: Data table, bold stats, high contrast**


## Gustilo Classification Grades Open Fractures and Drives Antibiotic Selection

| Type | Wound | Antibiotics |
|------|-------|-------------|
| **I** | <1 cm, clean | Cefazolin |
| **II** | 1-10 cm | Cefazolin |
| **IIIA** | >10 cm, covered | Cefazolin + aminoglycoside |
| **IIIB** | >10 cm, uncovered | + flap coverage |
| **IIIC** | Vascular injury | + vascular repair |

- All: tetanus, abx within 1h, debridement

**[KEY STAT: IIIC = vascular injury = highest amputation rate]**

> **Bottom Line:** Wound size + soft tissue + vascular status determines grade and antibiotics


**Sources:**
- [19] StatPearls
- [20] Gustilo 1976

<!-- Speaker Notes: The Gustilo classification for open fractures is tested because it determines antibiotic selection and predicts outcome, particularly amputation risk. Open fractures are classified by wound size, degree of contamination, soft tissue coverage, and presence of vascular injury. Type I fractures have a wound less than 1 cm with minimal contamination and are treated with cefazolin alone, targeting gram-positive skin flora. Type II fractures have wounds between 1 and 10 cm with moderate soft tissue damage, also treated with cefazolin. Type III fractures are subdivided into three categories. Type IIIA has wounds greater than 10 cm but adequate soft tissue coverage for closure — these receive cefazolin plus an aminoglycoside (typically gentamicin) because the larger wound increases gram-negative contamination risk. Type IIIB also has wounds greater than 10 cm but with inadequate soft tissue coverage, requiring flap coverage in addition to dual antibiotics. Type IIIC is defined by vascular injury requiring repair, regardless of wound size, and carries the highest amputation rate. Several management principles apply to all open fractures. Tetanus prophylaxis is administered based on immunization status. Antibiotics should be given within 1 hour of presentation — delay in antibiotic administration significantly increases infection rates. Operative debridement and irrigation should occur within 6 to 24 hours. The fracture should be stabilized, typically with external fixation initially for severely contaminated or unstable wounds. The key shelf teaching point is the transition from Type II to Type IIIA: this is where gram-negative coverage (aminoglycoside) is added. Farm injuries or those with significant soil contamination may also receive penicillin for Clostridium coverage. > **Shelf Tip:** The shelf tests Gustilo classification by describing an open fracture and asking which antibiotics. The decision point is wound size greater than 10 cm — that is when you add the aminoglycoside. If vascular injury is present, it is always IIIC regardless of wound size. -->

---

<!-- type: Content -->

**Gamma instruction: Professional layout, bullet hierarchy, sources**


## Fat Embolism Presents 24-72 Hours Post-Fracture with a Classic Triad

- **Timing:** 24-72h post long bone/pelvic fracture
- **Triad:** respiratory distress + confusion + petechial rash
- **Petechiae** on chest, axillae, conjunctivae
- **Rx:** supportive; **prevention** = early fracture fixation

**[KEY STAT: Triad = dyspnea + confusion + petechiae, 24-72h]**

> **Bottom Line:** Petechiae + confusion + dyspnea days after fracture = fat embolism


**Sources:**
- [19] StatPearls
- [21] StatPearls

<!-- Speaker Notes: Fat embolism syndrome is tested on the shelf because it has a distinctive clinical presentation with a specific time course that differentiates it from other post-traumatic complications. The syndrome occurs 24 to 72 hours after long bone or pelvic fractures, which is a critical timing detail. Fat globules from the bone marrow enter the venous circulation through disrupted medullary vessels and travel to the pulmonary vasculature. In the lungs, they cause mechanical obstruction and inflammatory injury, producing respiratory distress. A proportion of fat globules either pass through the pulmonary capillary bed or cross a patent foramen ovale to enter the systemic circulation, where they can lodge in cerebral and dermal vessels. The classic triad is respiratory distress (dyspnea, tachypnea, hypoxia from pulmonary fat embolization), neurologic changes (confusion, agitation, altered mental status from cerebral fat embolization), and petechial rash in a characteristic distribution on the chest, axillae, and conjunctivae. The petechial rash is pathognomonic and results from fat globule obstruction of dermal capillaries with platelet consumption. It is present in approximately 50-60% of cases and is the most specific finding. The diagnosis is clinical — there is no definitive laboratory test. Bronchoalveolar lavage showing fat-laden macrophages and retinal examination showing fat emboli can support the diagnosis. Treatment is supportive with supplemental oxygen and mechanical ventilation as needed. There is no specific pharmacologic therapy. Prevention through early fixation of long bone fractures (within 24 hours) significantly reduces the incidence of fat embolism syndrome by stabilizing the fracture and reducing ongoing marrow fat release into the circulation. > **Shelf Tip:** The timing is the key to the diagnosis. When a stem describes a patient who was stable after a femur fracture and develops confusion plus dyspnea plus a rash 2 days later, the answer is fat embolism syndrome. The 24-72 hour delay is what distinguishes this from pulmonary embolism or pneumonia. -->

