<!-- type: Content -->

**Gamma instruction: Professional layout, bullet hierarchy, sources**


## Damage Control Surgery Saves Lives by Treating Physiology Before Anatomy

- **Phase 1:** hemorrhage + contamination control (<60 min)
- **Phase 2:** rewarm, correct coagulopathy
- **Phase 3 (24-72h):** definitive repair
- **Trigger:** ≥2 of lethal triad (temp/pH/INR)

**[KEY STAT: Lethal triad = damage control, not repair]**

> **Bottom Line:** Fix physiology first, anatomy second — abbreviated surgery saves lives


**Sources:**
- [5] ATLS 2025
- [15] [Eastridge 2001](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23192066/)
- [22] [Holcomb 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25647203/)

<!-- Speaker Notes: Damage control surgery is a paradigm shift in trauma management that prioritizes correcting physiologic derangement over completing anatomic repair. The concept recognizes that the lethal triad of hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy creates a self-reinforcing cycle that kills patients on the operating table during prolonged definitive procedures. The trigger for damage control is the presence of any two elements of the lethal triad: core temperature below 35 degrees Celsius, pH below 7.2, and clinical coagulopathy (typically INR greater than 1.5 or non-surgical bleeding). When these criteria are met, attempting a definitive repair is more dangerous than an abbreviated operation. Phase one occurs in the operating room and should take less than 60 minutes. The goals are limited: control hemorrhage (packing, ligation, shunting) and control contamination (stapling off injured bowel, diverting enteric contents). The abdomen is temporarily closed, typically with a negative pressure wound therapy system or Bogota bag. No anastomoses, no complex repairs. Phase two occurs in the ICU and focuses on breaking the lethal triad: active rewarming to normalize temperature, blood product transfusion and factor correction to reverse coagulopathy, and volume resuscitation plus vasopressor support to correct acidosis. This phase typically takes 24 to 72 hours until the patient's physiology normalizes. Phase three returns to the operating room for definitive repair once the lethal triad has been corrected: bowel anastomosis, complex vascular repair, and definitive abdominal closure. The key teaching point is that damage control is a deliberate strategic decision, not a failure of operative technique. > **Shelf Tip:** When a stem describes a trauma patient in the OR with hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy, the answer is damage control (pack and close), not definitive repair. The shelf tests whether you recognize the lethal triad as the trigger. -->

---

<!-- type: MCQ -->

**Gamma instruction: Quiz card, A-D options, highlight correct answer**


## 30M GSW abdomen. OR: liver laceration + small bowel injuries. Temp 34.2, pH 7.18, INR 2.1. Best approach?

A. Complete liver repair and bowel anastomosis

B. **Pack liver, resect/staple bowel, temporary closure**

C. Pack liver only, leave bowel injuries

D. Close abdomen and manage conservatively

> **Bottom Line:** All three elements of lethal triad present = damage control

<!-- Speaker Notes: This question presents the classic damage control surgery scenario with all three elements of the lethal triad present: hypothermia (34.2 degrees Celsius, below 35), acidosis (pH 7.18, below 7.2), and coagulopathy (INR 2.1, well above normal). The patient has both a liver laceration and small bowel injuries from a gunshot wound. Option A, complete liver repair and bowel anastomosis, is the definitive repair that would be appropriate if the patient were physiologically normal. However, performing a complex hepatic repair and bowel anastomosis in the setting of the lethal triad will result in worsening coagulopathy from ongoing blood loss during the prolonged procedure, failed anastomosis from tissue edema and poor perfusion, and likely death on the table. Option B is correct: pack the liver to control hemorrhage (liver packing is one of the most effective damage control techniques), resect the injured bowel segments and staple the ends (controlling contamination without creating an anastomosis that will fail), and temporarily close the abdomen. The patient then goes to the ICU for phase two resuscitation. Option C is wrong because leaving bowel injuries unaddressed allows ongoing fecal contamination of the peritoneum, which will cause sepsis and death. Damage control controls BOTH hemorrhage and contamination. Option D is nonsensical — the patient has ongoing intra-abdominal injuries that require operative management. The teaching point is that damage control addresses all sources of hemorrhage and contamination while avoiding time-consuming definitive repairs. > **Shelf Tip:** Count the lethal triad elements in the stem. If two or more are present, the answer is always damage control. The shelf will tempt you with definitive repair — resist it. -->

---

<!-- type: Content -->

**Gamma instruction: Professional layout, bullet hierarchy, sources**


## Damage Control: All Three Elements of Lethal Triad Present — Abbreviated Surgery Saves Lives

- **Answer: B — Pack, staple, close**
- T34.2 / pH 7.18 / INR 2.1 = lethal triad
- Phase 1: pack, staple, close
- Phase 2: rewarm + correct
- Phase 3: definitive repair

**[KEY STAT: Full lethal triad = damage control]**

> **Bottom Line:** Lethal triad = pack, staple, close, resuscitate, then return


**Sources:**
- [5] ATLS 2025
- [15] [Eastridge 2001](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23192066/)
- [22] [Holcomb 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25647203/)

<!-- Speaker Notes: The correct answer is B, pack the liver, resect and staple the bowel, and perform temporary abdominal closure. This is textbook damage control surgery. Let us review why each step is necessary and why the other options are wrong. Packing the liver controls hemorrhage without requiring a complex hepatic repair. Perihepatic packing is remarkably effective for controlling venous bleeding from hepatic lacerations, and the packs provide tamponade while the patient resuscitates in the ICU. The packs are removed during the phase three definitive operation. Resecting and stapling the injured bowel segments controls contamination by preventing ongoing fecal spillage into the peritoneum. The bowel ends are stapled shut — no anastomosis is created because anastomoses made in the setting of hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy have an extremely high leak rate due to tissue edema and impaired healing. The anastomosis is deferred to phase three when the patient's physiology has normalized. Temporary abdominal closure allows for bowel edema (which is inevitable after massive resuscitation) without causing abdominal compartment syndrome. A negative pressure wound therapy system or Bogota bag is applied, and the abdomen is formally closed during a subsequent operation. The lethal triad parameters in this stem are all clearly abnormal: temperature 34.2 (hypothermia), pH 7.18 (severe metabolic acidosis from hemorrhagic shock), and INR 2.1 (coagulopathy from both consumption and dilution). Attempting definitive repair with these numbers would result in a prolonged operation during which the patient's physiology spirals further, ultimately leading to death on the table or shortly after in the ICU. -->

