## 15 Shelf Pearls: One Fact, One Question Pattern

| # | Key Pearls |
|---|-----------|
| 1-5 | Full-thickness = PAINLESS; PTX = clinical; biconvex = epidural; brady = neurogenic; Parkland = burn time |
| 6-10 | GSW = OR; Zone 3 = never explore; passive stretch = compartment; meatus = RUG; vaccinate |
| 11-15 | EDT ~15%; Beck = tamponade; SBP <90 = 2x TBI; fat embolism 24-72h; rib fx = abuse |

**[KEY STAT: These 15 facts represent the most commonly tested trauma shelf concepts]**

> **Bottom Line:** Pattern recognition of these 15 pearls covers the majority of shelf trauma questions

**Sources:** [1-23]

<!-- Speaker Notes: This slide consolidates the 15 highest-yield trauma facts from the entire presentation into a rapid-review format. Each pearl is paired with the way the shelf typically tests it, so you can recognize the question pattern before you even read the answer choices. Pearl 1: full thickness burns are painless because nerve endings are destroyed. The shelf presents a severe burn with no pain and asks about depth. Pearl 2: tension pneumothorax is a clinical diagnosis treated immediately. The shelf offers CXR as a next step — do not order imaging for tension PTX. Pearl 3: epidural is biconvex and subdural is crescent on CT. The shelf shows an image and asks for the diagnosis. Pearl 4: neurogenic shock presents with bradycardia and hypotension. The shelf asks you to differentiate from hemorrhagic shock. Pearl 5: Parkland formula calculates from the time of burn, not arrival. The shelf gives different times to test this. Pearl 6: GSW to abdomen goes directly to OR. The shelf offers CT as a distractor. Pearl 7: Zone 3 pelvic hematoma in blunt trauma is never explored. Pearl 8: pain with passive stretch is the earliest compartment syndrome sign. Pearl 9: blood at meatus requires RUG before Foley. Pearl 10: post-splenectomy requires vaccination against encapsulated organisms. Pearl 11: EDT survival is 15% for penetrating cardiac and 1.5% for blunt. Pearl 12: Beck triad defines cardiac tamponade. Pearl 13: SBP below 90 doubles TBI mortality. Pearl 14: fat embolism presents 24-72 hours post-fracture. Pearl 15: pediatric rib fractures indicate abuse because children have compliant chest walls. > **Shelf Tip:** Print this slide. Review it the morning of the exam. These 15 patterns cover the majority of trauma shelf questions. -->

